        Official Singles Chart on 22/5/2020

        22 May 2020 - 28 May 2020

        The Official UK Singles Chart reflects the UKs biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1 and MTV, the Top 100 is published exclusively on OfficialCharts.com. View the biggest songs of 2024 so far.

        Getting to the charts late today, but anyway, lets go. Rockstar clings on for another week despite having no video, somehow Stuck With U and GOOBA stay in the top 10, and we have 12 new entries to have a peek at! So lets get right in, using the same format as last week despite how unreadable it may be, to get past the spam filter.
        Lets start with #96 Guys by the 1975, a band who never seem to fail to notch a charting song, and who have seemingly dipped their toes into all manner of genres across the year so far. However, after hearing this Im definitely gonna be looking forward to 1975 songs charting in the future, because frankly, this is great. Its a song which is absurdly sappy, completely unashamed to revel in unadulterated emotion, the singer pours his heart out for his fellow bandmates and declares you guys are the best things that ever happened to me. Its a beautiful sentiment delivered in a gorgeously soft vocal timbre, and over pillowy instrumentation that includes just a touch of fluttering pianos and string embellishments to create such a warm, enveloping mix. This song hits all the right notes, its definitely a blissful oasis in these strange times. For me, a decent 7/10. At #95 we have Bad Luck by SL. I have to say I was surprised to hear Kenny Beats tag. He does ok here, the beat is very lethargic, just a flute line and a slow knock, but its dynamic enough not to lose my interest. SL sounds half-asleep to match the beat. I can see how it could kind of work, but overall its just ok. Decent 5/10.
        At #91 we have Flex by Polo G and Juice WRLD, and yeah, this aint it. The production here is garbage, its completely lifeless and stiff, the guitar loop gets annoying, the bass is grating against it, overall it doesnt come together and sounds completely cheap. Juice WRLDs verse would be fine paired with some more organic production with more space in the mix, this completely suffocates him. And Polo G uses the same flow for the verse and chorus and sounds about as stiff as the beat underneath him. This is grating. Bad news, decent 4/10 and thats being charitable. At #85 we have Trillionaire by Future and YoungBoy Never Broke Again, and this isnt particularly good either. The production does the bare minimum, some melancholic keys and some bass thats somewhat suffocated, not much groove here. The main problem is the absence of a good hook to make this more interesting to listen to because without it, this is pretty tedious. Future and YoungBoy have no vocal chemistry and could pretty much switch out for each other. Its definitely better than Flex but, pretty much just filler, and not good filler either. Strong 4/10.
        At #82 we have X by the Jonas Brothers and KAROL G. Im gonna be pretty charitable towards this, because it has a REALLY strong hook. In fact, the whole song, from a songwriting point of view, has pop excellence written all over it, more writing like this and I wont feel like the Jonas Brothers reunion is so pointless anymore. The KAROL G feature was tasteful, the song has a danceable beat, the ingredients are here, but I cant help but feel like the production ruins this one. Again, as Ive said for other songs here, it feels lifeless, just a bit too artificial. We need a stronger bass groove here, the brass needs to be better incorporated, the sound isnt enveloping enough, its not tangible enough. For me, a strong 5/10. Probably with room to grow because the hook is great. One of the best Jonas Brothers reunion songs so far if not the best. At #81, Will by Joyner Lucas, and Im gonna assume its the remix with Will Smith that has this charting, so apologies if thats wrong. Anyway, Im seriously surprised by the quality of this. Will Smith spat an amazing verse, it really has to be heard to be believed. He sounds so genuine in everything hes saying, acting as a mentor to Joyner, mentioning how he too had idols, detailing his career so far. He really makes the listener root for him, relish in his successes, every line he delivers flawlessly, he sounds like he really means what hes saying. This isnt just a phoned in verse, he really tried here to deliver something honest and heartfelt and it really worked, and his dynamic flows and vocal delivery are too. The production is standard for a hype anthem, a distorted trap knock that definitely has more bounce than some other songs were reviewed today. Im not a big fan of Joyner Lucas, but he only handles the hook so theres nothing to complain about. For me, a strong 6/10. Good stuff.
        At #78: Play Date by Melanie Martinez. Im gonna be honest and say I have no idea why this song is blowing up now and its 4 years old! The more important thing though is that its not at all good. The lullaby-like production isnt as cute as she thinks it is, her heavily autotuned vocals remove all personality from her voice and what personality remains is grating. The lyrics with their analogies to toys are really trite and boring and the sentiment of the song is petty and not in the way you can root for. This is just annoying to listen to. For its competency as a song (its not an assault on the ears), this is a decent 4/10. But I dont want to hear this ever again and if I do its score will probably plummet further. At #75 we have Surrender by Natalie Taylor. This song is 3 years old and all, but I feel like Ive heard it before so Im gonna assume this is here courtesy of TikTok. Anyway, Taylors vocal performance is decent in a pretty standard melancholic song with an ok hook. The production seems quite basic, overall doesnt seem polished enough to really hit. The production is veryroyalty-free, perhaps. Theres the kernel of a good song here, but for the moment, its just ok. Light 5/10.
        At #65 we have Lose Somebody by Kygo and OneRepublic, and, well, Ive made it no secret that Im about the furthest possible thing from a Kygo fan. However, this is definitely one of his least detestable songs in a while. The piano build up is very tried and true, it works, the hook is pretty strong. However, to my surprise, all this momentum wasnt instantly ruined with a mid-paced drop and distorted vocal snippets all over the place, Kygos calling card for sucking any and all life out of a song. Instead we get a second verse, and when the drop does come, its far more tasteful and puts the vocals much more front-and-centre. This reminds me a bit of the heel turn Marshmello recently provided, but a little better. This is inoffensive. Decent 5/10. At #59 we have Solitaires by Future and Travis Scott, and yeah, not good. The vocals are way too high in the mix for some reason, the beat is grating and just sounds tinny and flat, it compliments neither artist. The hook is garbage, theres no focus, no structure to the song. This is just a headache. Decent 4/10.
        At #43 we have Think About Things by Dai Freyr. Ill admit to not being plugged into Eurovision this year, which is rather unlike me, in fact I thought it was cancelled completely. There was still enough hype around the Icelandic song though, one of the favourites, that its managed to chart. Sadly, however, I dont like it. The production here is so rigid that there really is no groove to this. Its hard to explain it, but despite the prominence of the bass in the mix, the up-tempo beat just feels so square, and I hate to use the word again but, lifeless. Theres a cute energy to the song, I like the vocals, I like the progression of the song, I just really think the production here fails spectacularly and completely squanders this songs chances. It doesnt make the song difficult to listen to or anything, it more just makes it completely flat and unevocative. A light 5/10 for me, about as middling as you can get. Finally, we have Daisies by Katy Perry at #37, a pretty low debut for her. The song itself is ok, Perrys vocal performance is pretty strong, the production is ok, weve got a nice touch of guitar and some skittering percussion. The song never really gets off the ground though, theres no build up to the final chorus which provides a payoff which doesnt feel earned. Its a song that just doesnt feel like it gets off on the right foot, even if there are elements of it that are fine enough. Its not offensive though. Decent 5/10 for me.
        That leaves me giving best of the week handily to Guys and worst of the week is Flex, but good god is Melanie Martinez lucky I didnt give it to her. Some real stinkers this week that I hope dont stick around, but some good stuff too. Not a terrible week. Anyway, thanks for reading, have a good one!

        WEEKLY CHART REVIEW (22/05/2020 - 28/05/2020)

        Honestly, this weeks been so quieter than recent charts! Im actually surprised as to how little I have to say about this one, haha. :P

        Anyway, its cool to see Rockstar get a second week at #1, but this shouldnt come as a surprise to anybody! Its clearly dominant on both Spotify & Apple Music, but while radio & sales arent on the same level as its streaming, theyre a lot better than youd expect for these two artists. That being said, Im looking at how big this is becoming internationally & it might turn into a global hit for at least a few weeks, which is very rare for a trap song, especially heading into the summer!

        Was really rooting for Say So to go all the way though, given how I love both the original & the Nicki Minaj remix! Might even be one of my favourite songs of 2020 at this point.

        That said, I also put this songs viral success down to TikTok & its this streaming service thats also causing a lot of slow burners on the chart! The thing is, ACR doesnt affect these kind of songs, because they have enough momentum to somehow avoid declining in performance for three consecutive weeks, which is why youve got songs like Death Bed & If The World Was Ending that probably havent peaked in chart position just yet. Of course, you could argue these songs are as big as they are now thanks to how much people can relate to them under the current circumstances & Im not sure exactly how much further theyll get, but hey, I certainly dont mind them being here!

        Im also loving Rover now breaking into the Top 5! Flowers going Top 10 next week possibly? :)

        Outside of that, its awesome to see This City move up in the Top 20! Honestly, this one has been growing on me a lot lately, although I prefer the radio edit (Luca Schreiner) even more than the original! Im also happy that Dont Need Love & Breaking Me are there too, although Ive kind of moved on from the latter song as Ive known about it for like four months now. Still, if its going to become the next dance smash, better late than never! Surprised to see Boss B**ch as the highest climber of the week, but Im certainly not complaining. Kings & Queens also hitting a new peak is an even more awesome thing to see!

        As for the new entries, theyre both low down & I dont have a ton to say about them, so Ill blast through both of them quick.

        Starting with Party Girl... well, I actually dont mind the blend of the fuzzy trap beat over the scattered pianos, even if the latter struggles to ever find any sense of a melody. That being said, Im not all that impressed by the mixing around the vocals of StaySolidRocky, nor his voice in general sadly! Besides, this kind of content is really starting to get overused in rap songs & besides, I feel that Arizona Zervas did this better in Roxanne (even if that song hasnt aged amazingly well). As for this, not precisely bad, but Im probably going to forget this exists by the time I post my next review. Light 5/10!

        Then weve got Daisies by Katy Perry just about sneaking in! Look, for as hard as I can see that Katy Perry is trying to keep her mainstream success going in 2020, its barely working at best at this point. Ive seen some critics try to compare this song to Roar (a hit of hers that I still adore to this day) with its motivational lyrics about getting up after getting knocked off the ground, but that comparison would be more deserving if the production was actually empowering too, which it unfortunately isnt, because we never really get a climax or anything to take away from it thatll last long-term. I dont even deny that theres a lot of sincerity in Katys delivery either, but her vocals can sound really strained at times, especially at the end of each hook & it can sound really uncomfortable at points! Overall. itll fill pop radio for a while, but dont expect this to stick around for very long at all, so for me, light 6/10.

        The last one is Secrets by Regard & Raye! Believe it or not, while were only at #30, this is actually the highest new entry of the week, thats it already. Although, it might actually wind up being the best of the three! Dont you just find that Rayes vocals are just made for slower club jams? Thats always where shes sounded the most convincing & it really shows here! She can really capture the paranoia of a guy potentially cheating on her really well, even by sounding trembly at points for added effect. Then again, a big part of that is helped by that funky & polished debut! Shame were probably not going to get the chance to hear this at clubs & festivals over the summer, but hey, the least we can do is get it up the charts. Im giving this a solid 8/10 for now!

        Wait a minute?! Think About Things almost made the Top 40?! Thats incredible! Iceland really couldve won Eurovision 2020 if it wasnt cancelled.

        As for next week, I imagine The 1975 will edge out Suga of BTS for the #1 album next week! However, despite how big that new Gaga & Ariana collaboration will be, as well as Doja Cats remix of In Your Eyes causing an inevitable boost, I dont see either of them being powerful enough to be a threat to Rockstar, but they might end up in the Top 10 at least. Spoiler: Ill be saying really positive things about both next week!

        Thats it from me! Dont forget the Emoji Challenge coming up shortly.

        Enjoy the Bank Holiday weekend everyone! :D

        R
